summary:
"This book is undertaking a less privileged scientific approach in the contemporary Romanian and international historiography due to the lack of concern on the position assumed by Romania during the Sino-Soviet split. The aims of this research are to capture, as objectively as possible from the point of view of the Washington decision-makers, Romania's attitude in the context of the collapse of the Sino-Soviet relations, and the reasons which led to the reconfiguration of the Romanian state's position in the Communist bloc. Here are the several benefits of taking up this topic: 
- the process-oriented and fact-driven account of the elements that contributed to the decline of the Sino-Soviet relations; 
- the emphasis on the different viewpoints promoted by the decision-makers in Bucharest; 
- the pointing out, by means of a comparative analysis grid, of the boundaries of Romania’s independent stance in its relations with Moscow; 
- the outline of the role of “mediator” assumed by the Romanian state in this conflict; 
- the highlight of Romania’s attempts to facilitate the Sino-American rapprochement through a “Romanian channel” of communication with Beijing;
- the illustration of the impact of the Sino-Soviet disputes on the functioning of the bipolar system."
